    <segment id="1" parent="4" relname="background"> 
Ones intuition is defined as the act or faculty of knowing or sensing without the use of 
rational processes; immediate cognition (yourdictionary.com).</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="23" relname="span">  As computing evolved 
from the black and white text-based DOS environment to the colorful world of Graphical 
User Interface,</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="19" relname="span"> many applications have been praised to be natural, user-friendly, and 
intuitive.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="29" relname="span">  However, the mere fact that an environment is GUI based does not mean that 
it is intuitive.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="22" relname="span">  In many cases the term intuitiveness has been used in scenarios where it 
took time to develop some sense or knowledge of the system.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="nonvolitional-result">  Consequently, this is 
contrary to the true meaning of the word intuitive, which is having immediate 
cognition.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="20" relname="span">  Branding a product as being intuitive may force developers to oversimplify 
the product or even prevent further advancement;</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="8" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> since any newly added feature might 
not be intuitive because it is not familiar (Raskin, 1994).</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="15" relname="concession">  

Though the term has been used as a gimmick by marketers, </segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="30" relname="span">I think it can be a useful 
concept for designers in releasing systems that would be used by people with all levels of 
experience.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="27" relname="span">  It is important to measure intuitiveness when introducing a totally new 
system</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="21" relname="conjunction"> where time and satisfaction is a concern,</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="21" relname="conjunction"> and where the user of the new system 
accomplished the same task before by a completely different method.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="26" relname="span">  Examples of 
these systems include automated check-in machines at airports, and self-checkout 
cashiers machine at stores.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="25" relname="span">  Here the first encounter with the user must be a success</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="12" relname="antithesis"> or 
else the implementation of the system is a failure.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="2" relname="joint">  Intuitiveness can be measured in a 
control environment by recording completion times of task and tracking how many times 
users ask for help.</segment>
